#X text 413 40 Using [cos~] instead of [sin~] gives us a different resulting sonority \, plus a difference in behaviour \, as the output is 1 for an amplitude of zero! In practical terms \, it generates DC Offset and we need to filter it out with a highpass (since the DC component is a frequency of 0Hz). As for the sound quality \, it sounds an octave higher. This is because it is mirrored around the horizontal axis and it's kinda like a full rectification as we'll see., f 51;
#X obj 578 262 f2s~;
#X obj 662 781 expr~ $v1 * (27 + pow($v1 \, 2)) / (27 + 9*pow($v1 \, 2));
#X obj 662 745 clip~ -3 3;
#X text 750 745 a more efficient approximation of 'tanh';
#X obj 662 709 *~;
#X obj 749 664 hsl 128 15 0 3 0 0 empty empty empty -2 -8 0 10 #dcdcdc #000000 #000000 0 1;
#X obj 746 686 nbx 5 14 -1e+37 1e+37 0 0 empty empty empty 0 -8 0 10 #dcdcdc #000000 #000000 0 256;
#X obj 662 673 osc~ 400;
#X obj 746 711 f2s~;
#X text 831 27 Here we have the plotted transfer functions for display., f 24;
#X obj 662 813 throw~ \$0-out;
#X text 32 64 Instead of a table \, we now use trigonometric functions as transfer functions. The "tanh" has already been used as a "soft clipping" distortion and it's the default mode of [drive~] that we'll revisit in detail soon. It returns valores from -1 a 1 asymptotically \, which means getting closer and closer but never really reaching it. But it does feel like 'hard clipping' with values beyond the -7.6 to 7.6 range., f 49;
#X text 89 705 Note that Vanilla's [cos~] and ELSE's [sin~] are actually implemented with an internal table lookup for efficiency. So it's like using a table reader under the hood. Using trigonometric functions (as well as other functions like 'power') can be more expensive in the CPU. For 'tanh' we sometimes the approximation function to the right. It's not a perfect emulation \, not trully asymptotical and actually hard clipped \, but it's more efficient. This is the soft clipper that is used inside the feedback loop of [moog~] by the way., f 75;
